  "introduction": "**The Mystery of the -OH Group**\n\n*Teacher Action:* Hold up two bottles (or show images). One labeled 'Ethanol' and one 'Phenol'.\n\n*Hook Question:* \"Both contain an -OH group. If I put them in water, ethanol dissolves but doesn't change litmus paper color. Phenol also dissolves but turns blue litmus red! Why? Is it the same molecule with a different name?\n\n*Inquiry:* Let's look at their skeletons. Where exactly is that OH attached? Today we will crack this code by learning how to classify these molecules based on where they live in the carbon world."
  ],
  "theory": {
    "overview": "Alcohols and phenols are organic compounds containing a hydroxyl (-OH) functional group. The critical distinction lies in whether the -OH is attached to an aliphatic (alkane-like) chain or directly to an aromatic benzene ring.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Alcohol: R-OH where R is an alkyl group (aliphatic).",
      "Phenol: Ar-OH where the OH is bonded directly to a benzene ring carbon.",
      "Classification of alcohols depends on the number of carbons attached to the C bearing the -OH."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "**1. Structural Distinction**\n- **Alcohols**: The general formula is R-OH. The oxygen atom is bonded to an sp3 hybridized carbon in a saturated chain.\n  *Example*: Ethanol (CH3CH2OH). Here, the -OH is on a CH2 group which is part of a straight chain.\n- **Phenols**: The general formula involves Ar-OH. The oxygen atom is bonded directly to an sp2 hybridized carbon that is part of a benzene ring.\n  *Example*: Phenol (C6H5OH). Here, the -OH replaces one H on the hexagonal aromatic ring.\n\n**2. Classification of Alcohols**\nTo predict reactivity, we classify alcohols based on the substitution level of the carbon holding the hydroxyl group:\n- **Primary (1°)**: The C-OH is attached to 0 or 1 other Carbon atom.\n  *Example*: Ethanol (CH3-**CH2**-OH). The CH2 has one neighbor (the methyl).\n- **Secondary (2°)**: The C-OH is attached to exactly two other Carbon atoms.\n  *Example*: Propan-2-ol (CH3-**CH**(OH)-**CH3**). The central carbon touches two others.\n- **Tertiary (3°)**: The C-OH is attached to three other Carbon atoms.\n  *Example*: tert-Butyl alcohol ((CH3)3C-OH). The central carbon touches three methyl groups.\n\n*Note on Nomenclature:* When naming, the suffix '-ol' replaces the final 'e' of the alkane. Numbering starts from the end closest to the -OH group."
  },
